JavaScript Temporal.PlainDate:

- A Temporal.PlainDate object represents a calendar date without a time.
- A Temporal.PlainDate is typically in ISO 8601 format ("2026-05-01").
- âš ï¸ Plain Dates are used for dates that remain the same regardless of time zone.
- âš ï¸ Plaind date is ideal for dates such as birthdays or holidays.


#) Create a PlainDate:
    - 1ï¸âƒ£ You can create a PlainDate from a string.
    - The Temporal.PlainDate.from() method creates a PlainDate object with no time zone:
            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17'); // 2026-05-17
    
        The Temporal.PlainDate.from()method above:
            -> Parses the input using ISO 8601 parsing rules
                ðŸ’¡ Parsing means validation pluss automatic conversion.
            -> Accepts strings: "2026-05-01"
            -> Accepts objects: { year:2026, month:5, day:1 }
            -> Accepts temporal: PlainDate
            -> Returns a calendar date without a time like 2026-05-17.
    
    - 2ï¸âƒ£ You can also create a PlainDate using year, month, and day values.
    - The Temporal.PlainDate() method creates a temporal PlainDate object with no time zone.
            const date = new Temporal.PlainDate(2026, 5, 17);   // 2026-05-17
        
        The Temporal.PlainDate() method above:
            -> Uses a constructor call
            -> Expects numeric arguments (year, month, day).
            -> Returns a calendar date without a time like 2026-05-17.
        
    - âš ï¸ When to Use Which?
        1ï¸âƒ£ Use new Temporal.PlainDate() when:
            -> You have trusted numeric values
            -> You want speed
            -> You want predictable construction
            -> You are doing date math
        2ï¸âƒ£ Use Temporal.PlainDate.from() when:
            -> You are handling user input (strings)
            -> You are handling external data (JSON)
            -> You want maximum flexibility


#) Get the Current Date:
    - Use Temporal.Now.plainDateISO() to get today's date.
            const today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();  // 2026-02-25


#) Add and Subtract Days:
    - Use the add() method to add time.
    - Use the subtract() method to subtract time.
    - âš ï¸ This does not change the original date.
            let date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17");   // 2026-05-17
            let nextWeek = date.add({ days: 7 });               // 2026-05-24

            let date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17");   // 2026-05-17
            let previousWeek = date.subtract({ days: 7 });      // 2026-05-10


#) Add Months or Years:
    - just like the days, you can add and subtract the months.
    - âš ï¸ This does not change the original date.
            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17"); // 2026-05-17
            const nextMonth = date.add({ months: 1 });          // 2026-06-17

            const date = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-17"); // 2026-05-17
            const nextMonth = date.subtract({ months: 1 });     // 2026-04-17
    
    - ðŸ’¡ Temporal handles month lengths automatically.


#) Compare Dates:
    - ðŸ’¡The compare() method returns -1, 0 or 1.
        -> -1 if date1 is before date2
        -> 0 if equal
        -> 1 if after

            // Create two Temporal objects
            const date1 = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2026-05-01");
            const date2 = Temporal.PlainDate.from("2024-12-25");

            // Compare the dates
            let result = Temporal.PlainDate.compare(date1, date2);  // 1 (date1 is after date2)
    
    - ðŸ’¡You can also use equals() to check if two dates are the same.
        -> returns true or false
            
            const date1 = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            const date2 = Temporal.PlainDate.from('2026-05-17');
            let result = date1.equals(date2);   // true
    
    - ðŸ’¡ Why < and > Do Not Work?
        -> Temporal objects are objects, not primitive numbers.
        -> When you write (a < b), JavaScript tries to convert both objects to primitives.
        -> For Temporal objects, this does not produce a numeric timestamp like Dates.]

#) When to Use PlainDate:
    ðŸ‘‰ Any date without time
    ðŸ‘‰ Birthdays
    ðŸ‘‰ Deadlines
    ðŸ‘‰ Holidays
    ðŸ‘‰ Booking dates


#) Replace Date for Date-Only Values
    - With Date, you always get a time and time zone. This can create confusion when you only 
        need a calendar date. (see chapter 12 section 1. Creating Date Objects: examples)
    - PlainDate avoids this by storing only year, month, and day.